const Q_CRK_2015=[{"id": "objective>CRK>2015>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What was Herod's reaction when he heard the news about Jesus' birth?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He sent gifts</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was excited</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was troubled </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He became calm</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in Matthew 2:3, it is stated that when King Herod heard about the birth of Jesus, he was troubled. This was because he saw the newborn king as a threat to his throne.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : THE TRIALS OF JESUS BEFORE HEROD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"... Behold, I will bring evil upon you; I will utterly sweep you away...\"</strong> Elijah pronounced destruction on Ahab with the statement above his sin of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the killing of God's prophets</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">worship of other gods</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">going to war against Ramoth-gilead</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">greed, covetousness and murder</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement was made by Elijah to Ahab after Ahab and his wife Jezebel had Naboth killed in order to take possession of his vineyard. This is recorded in 1 Kings 21:21, hence the sin referred to here is greed, covetousness and murder.</div>", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : AHAB"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ruler of the synagogue whose child Jesus raised to life was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Zebedee</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A widow</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jarius</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A centurion </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the New Testament of the Bible, specifically in the books of Mark (5:21-43) and Luke (8:40-56), it is recorded that Jesus raised the daughter of Jairus, the ruler of the synagogue, from the dead. Therefore, the correct answer is Jairus.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : MIRACLES OF RESUSCITATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Amos, true religion entails</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">engaging in sacrifices and burnt offerings</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">being just and righteous</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fasting and praying always</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">engaging in holy feasts and assemblies</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Amos, specifically in Amos 5:24, the prophet Amos emphasizes that God desires justice and righteousness more than sacrifices and burnt offerings. This means that true religion, according to Amos, entails being just and righteous. Therefore, the correct answer is 'being just and righteous'.</div>", "topic": "SOCIAL JUSTICE, TRUE RELIGION AND DIVINE LOVE:SOCIAL JUSTICE AND TRUE RELIGION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul in Romans said that the righteousness of God has been manifested through faith in Jesus Christ for </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the exaltation of the authority</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the cleansing of the damned</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the dead in christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">all those who believe</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Romans 3:22, Paul states that the righteousness of God has been manifested through faith in Jesus Christ for all those who believe. This means that God's righteousness is revealed and given to all who have faith in Jesus Christ, regardless of their past sins or current circumstances. This righteousness is not earned or achieved, but is a gift from God that is received through faith.</div>", "topic": "JUSTIFICATION BY FAITH : MEANING AND BASIC CONDITIONS FOR JUSTIFICATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"I tell you, if these were silent, the very stones would cry out.\"</strong>  <br/> Jesus'statement above was made when</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was rebuked by the Pharisees for eating with sinners</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The scribes and the chief priest came to arrest Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He consoled a woman on His way to the cross</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Pharisees asked Him to rebuke His disciples</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"I tell you, if these were silent, the very stones would cry out.\" was made by Jesus during His triumphal entry into Jerusalem, as recorded in Luke 19:40. The Pharisees had asked Jesus to rebuke His disciples for their loud praises, to which Jesus responded that if they were to keep quiet, the stones would cry out. This was a declaration of His messiahship and a rebuke to the religious leaders who failed to recognize Him as the Messiah.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE : TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Before Moses brought the Isrealites to meet God on Mount Sinai, he charged them to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">touch the mountain at the sight of smoke </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ensure they eat very well</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wash their garments and be consecrated</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mate with their wives for three days</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Exodus 19:10-11, before the Israelites met God on Mount Sinai, Moses was instructed by God to consecrate the people. This involved washing their clothes and preparing themselves for the third day when God would come down on Mount Sinai in the sight of all the people. Therefore, the correct answer is 'wash their garments and be consecrated'.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In His teaching about Himself, Jesus said the hireling is not a good shepherd because he</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">leaves the sheep and flees at the sight of danger</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">owns the sheep but does not care for them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cares for the sheep but does not discipline them </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is the gate-keeper who shuts the sheep out</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In John 10:12-13, Jesus describes the hireling (or hired hand) as someone who does not own the sheep and does not care for them. When he sees a wolf coming, he abandons the sheep and runs away. So the wolf attacks the flock and scatters it. The man runs away because he is a hired hand and cares nothing for the sheep. Therefore, the correct answer is 'leaves the sheep and flees at the sight of danger'.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE GOOD SHEPHERD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God displayed His supremacy when Ahab was king during the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">incidence of Naboth's vineyard</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">war with Ramoth-gilead</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inciting of Jehoshapat against him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">contest of Mount Carmel</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The contest of Mount Carmel was a significant event in the Bible where God displayed His supremacy. During the reign of King Ahab, there was a contest on Mount Carmel between the prophet Elijah, who was a prophet of God, and the prophets of Baal. Elijah challenged them to call on their god to light a sacrifice. When they failed, Elijah called on God, who immediately sent fire from heaven to consume the sacrifice. This event demonstrated God's supremacy over the false god Baal.</div>", "topic": "THE SUPREMACY OF GOD : RELIGIOUS TENSION AND THE POWER OF GOD ON MOUNT CARMEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In his teaching on effective prayer, James said that the prayer of faith would</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">influence the authority</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">heal and cleanse sins</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ensure salvation for the sick</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">enhance commitment to church</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of James, it is stated that 'the prayer of a righteous person is powerful and effective' (James 5:16). James also said that the prayer of faith will heal the sick and if they have sinned, they will be forgiven (James 5:15). Therefore, the prayer of faith, according to James, has the power to heal and cleanse sins.</div>", "topic": "EFFECTIVE PRAYER : THE REQUIREMENTS OF EFFECTIVE PRAYER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul in Thessalonians declared that at the second coming of the Lord, those who are alive will not precede those that are</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ignorant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">condemned</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">asleep</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faithful</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Thessalonians 4:15-17, Paul explains that those who are alive at the second coming of the Lord will not precede those who have died (or 'are asleep'). The dead in Christ will rise first, then those who are alive will be caught up together with them in the clouds to meet the Lord in the air.</div>", "topic": "THE SECOND COMING OF CHRIST : THE SIGNS OF THE COMING OF CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When Ezekiel ate the scroll that was given to him his call, it signified that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God would always go before him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his sins were forgiven</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he would never the hungry</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he was filled with God's word</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Ezekiel 3:1-3, God commands Ezekiel to eat a scroll, and it tasted as sweet as honey in his mouth. This signifies that Ezekiel was filled with God's word. He was to internalize God's word and then proclaim it to the people of Israel.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF EZEKIEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"...I will surely tear the kingdom from you and will give it to your servant...\"</strong>  <br/>  An unwise decision of Solomon that resulted in God making the pronouncement above was his</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dependence on other nations for supplies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">policy of forced labour</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">neglect of God for other gods</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">heavy taxation on the people</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The unwise decision of Solomon that led to God's pronouncement of tearing the kingdom from him was his neglect of God for other gods. Solomon's wives turned his heart after other gods, and his heart was not fully devoted to the Lord his God, as the heart of David his father had been. This is recorded in 1 Kings 11:4-11.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : UNWISE POLICIES OF SOLOMON AND REHOBOAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God fed the Isrealites with Manna at the wildernerss of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Zin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elim </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sinai </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sin</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God fed the Israelites with Manna in the wilderness of Sin. This is recorded in Exodus 16:1-36. The Israelites came to the wilderness of Sin, which is between Elim and Sinai, on the fifteenth day of the second month after they had departed from the land of Egypt. And the whole congregation of the people of Israel grumbled against Moses and Aaron in the wilderness, and the people of Israel said to them, 'Would that we had died by the hand of the Lord in the land of Egypt, when we sat by the meat pots and ate bread to the full, for you have brought us out into this wilderness to kill this whole assembly with hunger.' Then the Lord said to Moses, 'Behold, I am about to rain bread from heaven for you, and the people shall go out and gather a day's portion every day, that I may test them, whether they will walk in my law or not.'</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE :EXAMPLES OF ADAM, COLLECTION OF MANNA, THE GOLDEN CALF, MOSES AND SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"The very stone which the builders rejected has become the head of the corner\"</strong>  <br/>  The statement above in Peter was directed to those who</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not believe in Jesus' preciousness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">build the Temple of Jerusalem</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">don't offer spiritual sacrifice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are hard hearted against Jesus Christ</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"The very stone which the builders rejected has become the head of the corner\" is a metaphor used by Peter to describe Jesus Christ. The 'builders' in this context are the religious leaders and people who did not believe in Jesus' divinity and rejected him. However, Jesus, the 'stone', despite being rejected, has become the 'head of the corner', meaning the most important part or foundation of the spiritual building, which is the church. Therefore, the statement was directed to those who did not believe in Jesus' preciousness.</div>", "topic": "THE HOLY SPIRIT AND THE MISSION OF THE CHURCH : THE MISSION OF THE CHURCH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A good example of parental responsibility was demonstrated by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samuel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Eli</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Asa </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">King Asa was a descendant of King David and the third King of the Southern Kingdom of Judah. He did what was good and right in the eyes of the Lord.</div>", "topic": "PARENTAL RESPONSIBILITY : ASA"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Why did Pilate send Jesus to Herod during the trial?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus, as a Galilean was under Herod's jurisdiction</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pilate had no power to pass the death sentence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Herod's court was the last point before crucifixion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Herod had longed to see Jesus perform miracles</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pilate sent Jesus to Herod because Jesus was a Galilean and thus fell under Herod's jurisdiction. This is based on the historical context of the time where different regions were ruled by different leaders and a person was subject to the jurisdiction of the leader of their region.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIALS AND THE DEATH OF JESUS : THE TRIALS OF JESUS BEFORE HEROD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Who was the king that granted Nehemiah permission to go and rebuild Jerusalem?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Darius </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nebuchadnezzar </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Artaxerxes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cyrus</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The king that granted Nehemiah permission to go and rebuild Jerusalem was Artaxerxes. This is recorded in the Bible in the book of Nehemiah chapter 2. Nehemiah served as a cupbearer to King Artaxerxes and when the king noticed his sadness, Nehemiah explained the situation of Jerusalem and requested permission to go and rebuild it, which the king granted.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : RESPONSE TO THE STATE OF JUDAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"Shall pursue after this band? Shall I overtake them?\"</strong>  <br/>  David's dependence on God for direction is depicted in the statement above when.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Absalom had revolted against him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Saul was within his grasp</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Amalekites had raided Ziklag</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was to go against Goliath </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Shall pursue after this band? Shall I overtake them?\" was made by David when the Amalekites had raided Ziklag, his city, and taken away the women and children. David was seeking God's direction on whether to pursue them or not. This shows his dependence on God for direction.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A parable that teaches a lesson on the demands of the kingdom is that of the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lost coin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Weeds</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samaritan</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prodigal son</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable of the Weeds (also known as the parable of the Wheat and Tares) teaches a lesson on the demands of the kingdom. In this parable, Jesus explains that the kingdom of heaven may be compared to a man who sowed good seed in his field, but while his men were sleeping, his enemy came and sowed weeds among the wheat and went away. The lesson from this parable is that we should allow both the good and the bad to grow together until the harvest (end of the age), at which point the 'weeds' (those who do evil) will be separated from the 'wheat' (the righteous).</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES OF THE KINGDOM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul admonished the Romans to live a new life in Christ by yielding themselves to God as men who </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Have been brought from death to life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">will meet Christ in God's kingdom </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">will receive judgement on the last day</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">have suffered for the sake of the gospel</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Romans 6:13, Paul admonishes the Romans to yield themselves to God as those who have been brought from death to life. This is a metaphorical way of saying that they should live a new life in Christ, leaving behind their old sinful ways and living according to God's will.</div>", "topic": "NEW LIFE IN CHRIST : CONDITIONS AND BENEFITS OF NEW LIFE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An action that demonstrated Solomon's wisdom was his </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">judgement of the prostitute's child</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reliance on a medium</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">alliance with other nations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taxation policy for his building works</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Kings 3:16-28, Solomon demonstrated his wisdom in the judgement of the two women who claimed to be the mother of the same child. Solomon's wisdom was shown when he suggested to divide the living child in two, giving half to each woman. The real mother, out of love for her son, immediately offered to give up her claim to save her son's life. Solomon then knew who the real mother was. This story is often used to illustrate Solomon's wisdom.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : THE WISDOM OF SOLOMON"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Corinthians, Paul while defending himself advised believers to boast only of the things that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exhibit their authority</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">show their weakness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">display their exaltation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">depict their righteousness</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 2 Corinthians 12:5, Paul states that he will boast only about his weaknesses. This is because he believes that when he is weak, then he is strong, as his strength comes from God. This concept is a key part of Christian theology, emphasizing humility and reliance on God's power rather than one's own abilities.</div>", "topic": "THE GREAT CONFESSION : THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE GREAT CONFESSION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The most important aspect of the religious reforms of King Josiah was the </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">renewal of the covenant</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cleaning of the Temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discovery of the tomb of the man of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discovery of the book of the law</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">King Josiah's religious reforms were centered around the renewal of the covenant. This is recorded in 2 Kings 23, where Josiah gathers the people of Judah and Jerusalem and reads to them the Book of the Covenant that had been found in the temple. He then renews the covenant, pledging to follow the Lord and keep his commands with all his heart and soul. This act of renewing the covenant is the most significant aspect of his reforms, as it represents a commitment to return to the worship of God and the rejection of other gods.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : RENEWAL OF THE COVENANT"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cornelius who was converted and baptized by Peter was a </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">member of the Sanhedrin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">centurion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Gentile who persecuted the church</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">scribe</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cornelius, as described in the Bible (Acts 10), was a centurion in the Roman army. He was not a member of the Sanhedrin, a Gentile who persecuted the church, or a scribe. A centurion was a professional officer of the Roman army. Cornelius is known as the first Gentile to convert to Christianity.</div>", "topic": "MISSION TO THE GENTILES : CONVERSION OF CORNELIUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David was successful as a leader in Israel because </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he submitted to God's guidance </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of his training as a soldier</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of the love of his people</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of his life as a shepherd</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">David was successful as a leader in Israel because he submitted to God's guidance. This is evident in the Bible where David often sought God's guidance before making decisions (1 Samuel 30:8, 2 Samuel 2:1). While his training as a soldier, the love of his people, and his life as a shepherd contributed to his leadership, his submission to God's guidance was the primary reason for his success.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The action that portrayed Moses as a leader of the Israelites was his</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">request to Pharaoh to spare Israelite's sons</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disobedience to Pharaoh and escape</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">killing of an Egyptian who fought with a Hebrew </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">protection of the daughters of Jethro</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Moses was seen as a leader of the Israelites when he killed an Egyptian who was fighting with a Hebrew. This action showed his willingness to protect his people, even at the risk of his own life. This is a key characteristic of a leader, someone who is willing to put the needs of their people before their own.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : MOSES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"How is it that you have agreed together to tempt the spirit of the LORD...\"</strong>  <br/>  The statement above was made in reference to the greed of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Gehazi and Naaman</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ahab and Jezebel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Judas and the scribes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ananias and Sapphira</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"How is it that you have agreed together to tempt the spirit of the LORD...\" was made in reference to the greed of Ananias and Sapphira. In the book of Acts in the Bible, Ananias and Sapphira sold a piece of property and lied about the price they sold it for, keeping some of the money for themselves. This act of greed and deception was seen as tempting the spirit of the Lord.</div>", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The king who captured and drove the Isrealites into exile during the reign of Jehoiachin was </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nebuchadnezzar </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Darius</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cyrus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Artaxerxes</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The king who captured and drove the Israelites into exile during the reign of Jehoiachin was Nebuchadnezzar. This is recorded in the Bible in 2 Kings 24:10-16.</div>", "topic": "CONCERN FOR JUDAH : THE FALL OF JERUSALEM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nebuchadnezzar decreed that all his subjects should worship the image he had set up whenever they</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">desired something from him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">saw him stand before it </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">looked upon it</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">heard the sound of music</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nebuchadnezzar decreed that all his subjects should worship the image he had set up whenever they heard the sound of music. This is recorded in the Bible in Daniel 3:1-7.</div>", "topic": "FAITH, COURAGE AND PROTECTION : EXAMPLES OF DANIEL, SHADRACH, MESHACH AND ABEDNEGO"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"The Son of man must suffer many things, and be rejected by the elder...\"</strong>  <br/>  Jesus made the statement above after He</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cleansed the Temple</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">demanded to know who people thought He was</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taught on the Mount</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was asked by Pilate if He was the King of the Jews</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"The Son of man must suffer many things, and be rejected by the elder...\" was made by Jesus after Peter confessed Him as the Christ. This happened when Jesus asked His disciples, 'Who do people say that I am?' and then 'Who do you say that I am?' (Mark 8:27-30). Therefore, the correct answer is 'demanded to know who people thought He was'.</div>", "topic": "THE GREAT CONFESSION : THE OCCASION OF THE GREAT CONFESSION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">How old was Abraham when God appeared to him the second time?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">105 years</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">75 years</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">99 years</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">85 years</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Bible, specifically Genesis 17:1, God appeared to Abraham for the second time when he was 99 years old. Therefore, the correct answer is '99 years'.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ABRAHAM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"Leave the dead to bury their own dead...\"</strong>  <br/>  Jesus' statement above to the man He asked to follow Him was indicative of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His power over death</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His desire to save the man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the furtility of life</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the cost of discipleship</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Leave the dead to bury their own dead\" was made by Jesus to a man who wanted to follow Him but asked to first go and bury his father. Jesus was emphasizing the urgency and importance of spreading the Gospel, which is a key part of discipleship. Therefore, the statement is indicative of the cost of discipleship, which may require giving up personal desires or obligations.</div>", "topic": "DISCIPLESHIP : THE DEMANDS OF DISCIPLESHIP"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul in Romans advised believers to respect those in authority to avoid God's wrath and also for the sake of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">conscience</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">christ</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">others</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Romans 13:5, Paul advises believers to respect those in authority not only to avoid punishment but also for the sake of conscience. Conscience here refers to the inner sense of what is right or wrong in one's conduct or motives, impelling one toward right action. Therefore, respecting authority is not just about avoiding God's wrath, but also about maintaining a clear conscience.</div>", "topic": "CIVIC RESPONSIBILITY : THE NEED FOR OBEDIENCE TO AUTHORITY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"What is this conversation which you are holding with each other...\"</strong>  <br/>  Jesus made the statement above to Cleopas and the other disciple when</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they were on their way to Emmaus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He was about to be arrested</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they were gathered in a room after His resurrection</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He told them that somebody would betray Him</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement was made by Jesus to Cleopas and the other disciple when they were on their way to Emmaus. This is recorded in the Bible in the book of Luke 24:13-35. After His resurrection, Jesus appeared to two of his disciples who were walking from Jerusalem to Emmaus. They were discussing the events of the past few days (Jesus' crucifixion and reports of His resurrection) when Jesus Himself drew near and went with them, but their eyes were kept from recognizing Him. He asked them what they were discussing, hence the statement \"What is this conversation which you are holding with each other...\".</div>", "topic": "RESURRECTION, APPEARANCES AND ASCENSION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION AND APPEARANCE OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A key requirement for healing as exemplified by the disciple's inability to heal the epileptic boy is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">righteousness </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Power</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">humility</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Faith</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The key requirement for healing, as exemplified by the disciples' inability to heal the epileptic boy, is faith. This is recorded in the Bible in the book of Matthew 17:14-20. When the disciples asked Jesus why they could not drive the demon out of the boy, Jesus replied, \"Because you have so little faith. Truly I tell you, if you have faith as small as a mustard seed, you can say to this mountain, 'Move from here to there,' and it will move. Nothing will be impossible for you.\" Therefore, faith is the key requirement for healing.</div>", "topic": "FAITH, COURAGE AND PROTECTION : EXAMPLES OF DANIEL, SHADRACH, MESHACH AND ABEDNEGO"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to Paul in Philippians, Jesus demonstrated humility when He</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had pit on the possessed man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">likened Himself to God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">forgave those who crucified Him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">took the form of man</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Philippians, Apostle Paul explains that Jesus demonstrated humility by taking the form of a man. This is found in Philippians 2:5-8, where Paul describes how Jesus, despite being in the form of God, did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped, but emptied himself, by taking the form of a servant, being born in the likeness of men.</div>", "topic": "HUMILITY : MEANING AND REQUIREMENTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"Holy, holy, holy is the LORD of host...\"</strong>  <br/> The statement above was made in reference to the call of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ezekiel </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amos</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"Holy, holy, holy is the LORD of host...\" is made in reference to the call of Isaiah. This is found in Isaiah 6:3, where the seraphim around God's throne are described as calling to one another with these words. This vision and call led to Isaiah's prophetic ministry.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF ISAIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">For obeying His word, God rewarded Shiphrah and Puah with</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">families</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">positions</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">servants</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wealth</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Shiphrah and Puah were the two Hebrew midwives who feared God and did not do as the king of Egypt commanded, but let the male children live. As a reward for their obedience, God gave them families of their own (Exodus 1:15-21). Therefore, the correct answer is 'families'.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE : OBEDIENCE AND REWARDS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In his teaching on Spiritual gifts in Corinthians, Paul said that all gifts are inspired by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the same spirit </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prayer</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the individual's ability</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">grace</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Corinthians 12, Paul discusses spiritual gifts and emphasizes that they are all given by the same Spirit. He states in verse 4: 'There are different kinds of gifts, but the same Spirit distributes them.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'the same spirit'.</div>", "topic": "SPIRITUAL GIFTS : THE DIFFERENT SPIRITUAL GIFTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When David's son Absalom rebelled against him, David was forced to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">flee from Jerusalem</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">abdicate the throne</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">divide his kingdom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">surrender to him</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, 2 Samuel 15:14, when Absalom rebelled against his father David, David had to flee from Jerusalem to avoid confrontation with his son. He did not abdicate the throne, divide his kingdom or surrender to Absalom.</div>", "topic": "A MAN AFER GOD'S OWN HEART: DAVID'S SUBMISSION TO THE WILL OF GOD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>\"Go and stand in the temple and speak to the people all the words of this life.\"</strong>  <br/> The angel's statement above to Peter was after</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the murmuring of the Hellenists</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his release from prison</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">his vision of eating unclean meat </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he received the Holy spirit</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Acts 5:19-20, an angel of the Lord opened the prison doors and brought out the apostles, including Peter, and commanded them to go and stand in the temple and speak to the people all the words of this life. This happened after Peter's release from prison, not after the murmuring of the Hellenists, his vision of eating unclean meat, or after he received the Holy Spirit.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIANS AS JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST : HOW CHRISTIANS ARE JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In His sermon on the Mount, Jesus discouraged His listeners from laying up treasures on earth because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it would create enmity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they would not be respected </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">thieves would steal them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the earth would pass away</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Sermon on the Mount, Jesus discouraged His listeners from laying up treasures on earth because these earthly treasures are not permanent and can be stolen by thieves. This is recorded in Matthew 6:19-21, where Jesus says, 'Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moths and vermin destroy, and where thieves break in and steal. But store up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where moths and vermin do not destroy, and where thieves do not break in and steal. For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.' Therefore, the correct answer is option 3, 'thieves would steal them'.</div>", "topic": "SERMON ON THE MOUNT : THE DEMANDS OF THE KINGDOM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul returned Philemon's slave back to him to ensure that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Philemon forgave and accepted the slave</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the slave can complete his service time</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he would be welcome when he left prison</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he would boast of philemon's obedience</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Philemon in the New Testament, Paul returned a runaway slave named Onesimus to his master Philemon. Paul's intention was not to ensure that the slave completes his service time or to boast of Philemon's obedience. Instead, Paul's primary intention was to reconcile Philemon and Onesimus, urging Philemon to forgive and accept Onesimus not as a slave, but as a brother in Christ. Therefore, the correct answer is option 1, 'Philemon forgave and accepted the slave'.</div>", "topic": "FORGIVENESS : PAUL’S TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the prophets that prophesied hope for Isreal in spite of God's promise of punishment was</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amos</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Obadiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hosea</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah is known as the prophet of hope. Despite the dire circumstances and the impending doom that was to befall Israel due to their disobedience, Jeremiah gave them a message of hope. He prophesied that God would make a new covenant with them (Jeremiah 31:31-34).</div>", "topic": "PUNISHMENT AND HOPE : THE CONDITIONS FOR HOPE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The church that was commended for giving even when in extreme poverty was in</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Galatia</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Corinth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Macedonia</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Thessalonica</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The church in Macedonia, despite being in extreme poverty, was commended for their generosity. This is mentioned in 2 Corinthians 8:1-5, where Paul praises the Macedonian church for giving as much as they were able, and even beyond their ability, entirely on their own.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIAN GIVING : THE IMPORTANCE OF CHRISTIAN GIVING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>'...I am the LORD, and there is no other, besides me there is no God...'</strong>  <br/>  God's statement above through Isaiah depicts</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">assurance to Isaiah of His existence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Israel's acceptance of His Supremacy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His divine nature</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His sovereignty</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement '...I am the LORD, and there is no other, besides me there is no God...' is a declaration of God's sovereignty. Sovereignty refers to the supreme power or authority. In this context, God is asserting His supreme power and authority, stating that there is no other God besides Him.</div>", "topic": "THE SUPREMACY OF GOD : RELIGIOUS TENSION AND THE POWER OF GOD ON MOUNT CARMEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Believers today are partakers of the New Covenant through</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">partaking in baptism by immersion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the gift of the Spirit</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">adherence to all the sacraments</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">obedience to church leadership</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Believers today are partakers of the New Covenant through the gift of the Spirit. The New Covenant, as described in the Bible, is a new relationship between God and humans mediated by Jesus Christ, which necessarily includes all believers. This covenant is characterized by the outpouring of the Holy Spirit, which is the gift of the Spirit. Baptism, adherence to sacraments, and obedience to church leadership are all part of the Christian faith, but they are not the means by which believers partake in the New Covenant.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : THE NEW COVENANT"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's message through Jonah was to the people of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Joppa</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tarshish</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samaria </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nineveh</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jonah was a prophet in the Bible who was called by God to deliver a message to the people of Nineveh. Nineveh was a notoriously sinful city and God sent Jonah to prophesy its destruction unless the people repented. Therefore, the correct answer is Nineveh.</div>", "topic": "GOD'S MESSAGE TO NINEVEH: JONAH AND HIS MESSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2015>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amos is often referred to as a prophet of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">doom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">love</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hope</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">justice</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amos is often referred to as a prophet of justice. He was a shepherd and a farmer before God called him to be a prophet. Amos preached in the northern kingdom of Israel, condemning the injustices of the wealthy and powerful, and calling for justice for the poor and oppressed. Therefore, the correct answer is justice.</div>", "topic": "SOCIAL JUSTICE, TRUE RELIGION AND DIVINE LOVE:SOCIAL JUSTICE AND TRUE RELIGION"}];
